          "body": "God's reply to Solomon (1:11-12) is structured as a divine reading of the heart. Before granting anything, God names what Solomon *did not* ask for: riches, wealth, honor, the death of his enemies, long life (1:11). This is a remarkable inventory — precisely the things a new monarch ordinarily most desires. By itemizing the refusals, God makes the character of Solomon's request explicit: he asked for the tools of service, not the rewards of status. God then grants both the request and the unasked surplus. 'Wisdom and knowledge have been granted to you' (1:12) — the verb is passive, a divine bestowing — and then the list of what was refused becomes the list of what is added: riches, wealth, and honor unequaled among any king before or after. The theological principle is the one Jesus will name in Matthew 6:33 — seek first the kingdom of God and His righteousness, and all these things will be added. The Chronicler is not teaching prosperity theology; he is teaching that the properly ordered heart, one that seeks what serves God's people rather than what serves itself, receives from a generous God more than it was willing to ask."
