          "title": "The shadow at the chapter's edge — horses, Egypt, and Deuteronomy",
          "body": "The chapter does not end with the theophany. After Solomon returns to Jerusalem and the confirming note of verse 13, the Chronicler records three verses of commercial and military expansion: 1,400 chariots, 12,000 horsemen, horses from Egypt and Kue, trade at scale with the Hittites and Aram (1:14-17). The prose is matter-of-fact, almost ledger-like in tone. But the reader of Torah hears an alarm. Deuteronomy 17:16 is explicit: 'He shall not multiply horses for himself, nor shall he cause the people to return to Egypt to multiply horses.' The prohibition was not ceremonial; it was a ban on trusting military power and returning to the nation that enslaved Israel. The Chronicler records Solomon's horse-trade with Egypt without editorial condemnation — but his silence is eloquent. He has just finished narrating a king who asked for nothing self-serving, received wisdom from God, and was promised unequaled honor. The next paragraph shows that king doing the one thing the Law forbade his kingship to do. The seed of Solomon's later apostasy (1 Kings 11) is already being planted in verse 16 of his first chapter. The post-exilic reader who survived Babylon because of exactly this kind of covenant-drift would not have missed it."
